      = tag :img, :src => "/images/blue-bottle/pot-of-african-gamayo.jpg", :alt => "Pot of African Gamayo"
    
    %h3 Time to Get to Work
    
    %p After I was sufficiently caffeinated, I walked around to find a place to sit down and plug in my laptop. It was time to get real. While I walked around, I noticed the branded clothing adorned on people carrying laptop bags.. #{link_to "Square", "http://squareup.com"}, #{link_to "Zaarly", "http://zaarly.com"}, #{link_to "twitter", "http://twitter.com"}, etc... Logos of tech companies I follow were all around. Seemed like a good sign.
    
    %p I found a little cafe that had food, coffee... and power outlets!!! So, I got a table and plugged in. At first I was just re-checking in with folks I had reached out to earlier when I was brainstorming this idea. Writing emails and sending direct messages on twitter, I wanted to set some actual times to meet up. While I sorted some of this stuff out, I had a moment to check-in with some coworkers at #{link_to "Relevance", "http://thinkrelevance.com"} and do some project work. Then the emails started coming in.
    
    %p Here's what I lined up:
    
    %ul
      %li An evening to work with #{link_to "Chris Eppstein", "https://twitter.com/chriseppstein"}
      %li A day to work at #{link_to "UserVoice", "http://uservoice.com"}
      %li A day to work at #{link_to "Storenvy", "http://storenvy.com"}
      %li An evening, to hang out with #{link_to "Jay Robinson", "http://twitter.com/jayrobinson"}, a UX designer at #{link_to "Sencha", "http://sencha.com"}
    
    %h3 Lunch with Jeff Broderick &amp; Manolo Savi
    
    %p I started getting hungry. While I was reading some tweets, #{link_to "Jeff Broderick", "http://twitter.com/brdrck"}, a product designer I follow but have never met in person, sent out a tweet asking who wanted to join him and #{link_to "Manolo Savi", "http://twitter.com/manolosavi"} for lunch. I replied eagerly as this is what I was there for. This is why I wanted to keep my schedule loose... for adventure time!
    
    %p
      %a.avatar.brdrck{:href => "https://twitter.com/brdrck", :name => "Jeff Broderick"}
      %a.avatar.manolosavi{:href => "https://twitter.com/manolosavi", :name => "Manolo Savi"}
    
    %p I met with them, ate food and talked shop. It was interesting to hear what Jeff was doing. He wasn't working for anybody, he wasn't contracting... he was just partnered with some folks and was solely focused on building products that he wanted to design. He talked about his current project #{link_to "jump.tv", "http://jump.tv"} and how he wanted to only ship with features fully baked. You know, not just ship something to ship it and test... but really ship features that he feels good about. Features he feels look good, have nice interactions and then also provides value to the user and the business. He talked about minimizing distractions... thinking for the user instead of making them think. It was really cool!
    
    %p Manolo was here on a tour of his own before he goes back to school. I ran into both of these guys again while I was in town. For a big city, it seems that the circles are smaller than I had thought they might be. I had a great lunch! I talked about what I did, the tools I worked with... the types of tech that I've worked with at Relevance. I think I might have scared these guys a bit with my "Designers should learn to use the Terminal" bit, but overall it was a pretty good time.
    
    %p I was going to set up some time to work with Jeff on getting more familiar with the whole git/heroku deploy story and walk him through some of the stuff I have been using like #{link_to "middlebot", "http://github.com/michaelparenteau/middlebot"} and #{link_to "middleman", "http://middlemanapp.com"}, but time was limited and it just didn't line up.
    
    %p @brdrck - The offer still stands... if you want to do some remote pairing, I would be happy to do that if you are still interested. :)
    
    %h3 Cask - a Whiskey Heaven
    
    %p After lunch, as I was walking with Jeff &amp; Manolo, I noticed the sight of glorious whiskey... lots and lots of whiskey. #{link_to "Cask", "http://www.caskstore.com"} is what I would imagine a wizard's library to look like. The space was dark, wooded &amp; the shelves were organized with bottles of spirits from different regions and grain. I found an interesting bottle (#{link_to "Whistle Pig", "http://whistlepigwhiskey.com"}) and decided to bring it back to my friend who was putting me up for the week. I sent out a tweet #{link_to "@jgehtland", "http://twitter.com/jgehtland"}, our CEO at Relevance, with a photo showing some very rare whiskeys. He later requested the exact location of this fine gem &mdash; If you like whiskey and find yourself in SF, you should check it out. No, it's not the place where they sell kilts and serve booze (that actually exists)... but it is, no doubt, a good find!
    
